Research by the Foundation for International Training Aids Relief (FIST-Africa) found that in general women who have known individuals who aborted their unborn children tend to view abortion as safer than previously thought and more acceptable. Chibanda et al. (2007) found that some Zimbabwean men want family planning methods employed in their relationships due to their fear of the possibility that their partner may become pregnant as a result of their infidelity, but where inability to access contraceptive services prevents them from using them (pp. 16-19). Most couples in this study’s sample found sexual abstinence acceptable only for shorter periods, and a few women mentioned means other than abstinence (p. 17).
Some respondents indicated that commitment decreases with long periods of abstinence which dictates that lower risk-conducive behavior both in cases of contraception, as well as within committed relationships is advisable (Chibanda et al. 2007). Paden and Chongo (2003) found that among their study’s participants, the reference group for deciding what to do when abortion is required are health providers who have failed to provide services and infrequent homebased HIV counselors whose services do not reach them. Although they indicated a fear of dying from the abortion, Black et al.
